  "text": "The Rust trait solver obligation chain is a sophisticated system for resolving trait bounds and checking if types implement required traits. The chain flows through several key components:\n\n**Entry Point (SelectionContext)**: The obligation resolution begins in compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/mod.rs with the SelectionContext struct. The public `select()` method at line 285 is the entry point for monomorphic trait obligations, which delegates to `poly_select()` at line 253 for polymorphic obligations.\n\n**Obligation Stack Management**: The selection process creates a TraitObligationStack (defined at line 129 in mod.rs) to track nested obligations and prevent infinite recursion cycles. The stack maintains freshened trait predicates to detect recursive loops.\n\n**Candidate Assembly (candidate_assembly.rs)**: The core of the selection process happens in `assemble_candidates()` at line 27 of candidate_assembly.rs. This method collects all potential trait implementations that could satisfy an obligation, considering: impl trait bounds, caller-provided bounds, built-in traits (Copy, Clone, Sized, etc.), and lang items. The assembled candidates are returned as a SelectionCandidateSet.\n\n**Impl Matching (_match.rs and mod.rs)**: After candidate assembly, the `match_impl()` method (line 2502 in mod.rs) performs detailed matching to ensure an impl's type parameters unify with the obligation's predicates. This includes instantiating generic parameters and checking if the impl actually applies.\n\n**Candidate Evaluation and Winnowing**: The `candidate_from_obligation_no_cache()` method (line 357 in mod.rs) filters candidates through `filter_impls()` at line 417, evaluates their viability via `evaluate_candidate()`, and when multiple candidates remain, determines which is most specific using specialization rules.\n\n**Confirmation (confirmation.rs)**: Once a single candidate is selected, `confirm_candidate()` at line 34 of confirmation.rs verifies the selection by instantiating the candidate and computing any nested obligations that must also be satisfied. For user-defined impls, this means calling `confirm_impl_candidate()` which further applies the `rematch_impl()` method at line 442 of mod.rs.\n\n**ObligationForest Data Structure** (rustc_data_structures/src/obligation_forest/mod.rs): The fulfillment engine uses an ObligationForest (defined at line 152) as a tree-based data structure to track outstanding obligations. Each node tracks its obligation state, dependents, and parents. The forest efficiently manages cycles and dependencies among obligations.\n\n**FulfillmentContext Integration** (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/fulfill.rs): The FulfillmentContext struct at line 61 encapsulates an ObligationForest of PendingPredicateObligations. It drives the overall trait obligation resolution process by repeatedly processing obligations through the FulfillProcessor (line 252), which invokes SelectionContext::poly_select() at line 853. The `process_obligations()` method of ObligationForest at line 433 of obligation_forest/mod.rs returns ProcessResult enums (line 143): Unchanged (ambiguous), Changed (with subobligations), or Error.\n\n**Error Reporting** (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/mod.rs): When obligations fail, `report_fulfillment_errors()` at line 140 generates comprehensive diagnostics. This includes extracting the obligation cause chain (stored in each Obligation struct), providing suggestions for adding trait bounds or imports, and explaining why specific impls don't apply. Additional specialized error reporting is in fulfillment_errors.rs for detailed trait compatibility analysis.\n\n**Cache and Performance**: The selection context maintains selection and evaluation caches (SelectionCache and EvaluationCache defined in compiler/rustc_middle/src/traits/select.rs lines 15-18) keyed on environment and trait predicates to avoid redundant candidate assembly and evaluation.\n\nThe entire chain ensures that trait obligations are resolved deterministically while detecting ambiguities, providing helpful error messages, and optimizing through caching and specialization."
